Trans-generational trauma, where the symptoms of trauma can be taught to the next generation. Rhythm and regulation - It is the traditional healing of Black community, our beliefs and values, the traditions of dance and song help to regulate us.

Nurturing rhythm/rhythmic movement has a calming effect on the human nervous system, and a regulating effect on the human brain. It also help dysregulated parents like myself who are using this method.

Since she is 3.5 yo and developing her safety awareness, some of our rooms are ‘yes’ spaces, specifically for her where she can feel 99% safe and confident. Last October, she started to put the plug in the socket independently (obviously we were hesitant at first)

At 1.5-2 yo, she repeatedly turned power sockets with switches on/off under strict supervision, we often turned it off and calmly signed ‘leave it now’ for a few months before she lost interest. From the age of two, she started to follow safety guidelines and rules (eg only Dad and Mama turn the cooker on, she knows we can’t poke metal objects). It doesn’t mean she FULLY understand, it’s still risk. That’s why supervision/guidance are still required.

She uses her Bissell Featherweight Stick vacuum to develop her independence and concentration. She can able to choose, to make her own decisions on what to do and when to do it!

NOTE: it’s not for everyone (cordless vacuums are great!) When you are ready then allow your child who is also ready to put the plug in the socket and start vacuuming!

NOTE: my Mum acknowledged and apologised about my negative relationship with food resulting in me being sneaky. Remember it is NOT only caused by this experience.

I have an unhealthy relationship with food includes eating when I am not hungry: deal with negative emotions such as stress, fear, anxiety or feeling deprived, lead to feelings of guilt and shame.
Research - restricted children eat more high-calorie snack foods and are fatter than children who are allowed regular access the those foods.

During my college year (stressful time) and living with my Mum, I developed cravings and eat as much of them as I can and I sneaked and hid them because I simply avoid being shamed for overeating or eating ‘forbidden’ food.

We teach Miss O to understand that she is not defined by the foods she eats, allow her to eat when she is hungry and stop when she is full and let her to listen and respect her body. So it can help her to learn to eat more-nutritious, more-challenging foods at meals and snacks.

Instead of shaming (You will get fat!) or dismissing (Because I said so) or accusing (Did you eat it?) We validate her emotions while also setting firm, clear, and consistent boundaries is the key to us and her feeling seen, watched, and supported:
{Miss O walks to the pantry}
Dad: What do you want to get?
Miss O: Chocolate
Dad: Oh! You ate it today. You are so upset.. I know you want more but not today.

Dads, avoiding any conflicts would not be possible as we are humans. It’s what happens NEXT that matters. Losing our cool is part of life and an experience our children will have themselves

Of course when the conflict happens, repairing can be more difficult especially we may not feel fully seen by our parents in the past.

When repair happens after conflict, conflict in the family becomes much less scary and threatening for parent and child.

Simple tips - during and after the conflicts:

Just pause and give yourself a minute to breathe deeply or tell your child where you are, walk away, have a drink of water, and return once you’re calm

You and your child have to be calm enough.

ALWAYS apologise after you lost it - your child will learn effectively through modelled examples.

Tell your child how you feel about them 😘 show your compassion and kindness

#montessorichild #montessoriathome #validatingemotions #auslan #coda #reconnect #modelling #compassion #kindness #understandingthewhy #calmyourself

Note: it is not for everyone.

Like most parents, Mama and I are struggling during these night because we just want to have our time!

Miss O who is highly sensitive and 3yo has trouble with sleep because she has a very active mind.  It is so hard to calm down her racing thoughts, when her minds are busy processing everything that has gone on throughout the day. She needs to push, run, jump, laugh to calm her nervous system. 

Routine
This lets her know what is expected each night and makes our life a lot easier. Playing with Dad or Mama then reading books consistently.

Choices
Allow her to choose 3 books or pyjama so she feels respected.

Timing
The bedtime routine start early enough to ensure that there is NO RUSHING involved. Expects one hour… (God helps us) Netflix can wait 😉

How do you deal with this? Thank you!

It’s ok to cry in front of your child. Real men cry. Crying is not a weapon. Vulnerability is strength not weakness

If you have been feeling guilty about crying in front of your kids, no worries crying is actually really healthy for our bodies because the stress hormone is released in our tears! However if you are crying uncontrollably, it may be good idea to walk away or talk to your loved ones.

I cried in front of Miss O, it felt so weird but GREAT! I often cried in front of my wife, my friends, movies such as The Colour Purple.

Modelling coping skills: how to handle emotions when I have my emotions. Let Miss O sees it. I often ask her for a hug and as a result, when she is sad she asks me for a hug.

I sometime signed ‘oh s…’ in front of Miss O without realising. I was like eeek!

You don’t have to swear at home if you don’t want your children to swear 👍🏿

Benjamin Bergin, a cognitive scientist at the University of California San Diego found evidence that swearing actually may have some positive effects on children.

Research has found that children start swearing around age two. We think O may not fully understand the meaning of swear signs/words yet.

We can’t protect Miss O’s eyes and ears all the time, she will pick up these signs and words from angry hearing drivers, my Yorkshire friends, our neighbours etc anyway. We (hearing family member too) will educate her about swearing signs/words when she is older. If we forbid her, she will want to do it more! For us, she understands that while curse words are acceptable in our own home, they might not be welcome in other settings like in public or schools. Not like I intentionally swear when she is there, I sometime swear when I am in pain. Swearing helps relieve pain!

Obviously swearing is not always ok, O also need to understand the difference between swear signs/words and slurs and how some signs/words can hurt others.

#montessoriathome #montessoridad #language #personalchoice #realemotions #auslan #coda #relievingpain #teachingmoments #interestingsigns

All couples argue. Argument or disagreement is healthy in relationships. It is what helps couples move forward and grow. Of course we would feel so guilty if our children witnessed it.

Research from 2016 found that unresolved tensions after a parental disagreement are linked to increased anxiety, depression, and social phobia. A 2017 one showed that children whose parents resolved their conflicts had better coping skills. We checked in with Miss O, ensure she was ok and it was not her fault or responsibility.

HOWEVER fighting or name-calling etc are NOT acceptable, it will affect our children big time.. such as behaviour problem, depression or anxiety. They also have may greater reactivity to angry tones when in relationships or even friendships.

For Deaf children who are very sensitive to their hearing parents’ body language but may miss their healthy resolution so they may create their own narrative/assumptions. Their hearing siblingsin background has more chance of learning to better coping skills. Deaf children may be at very high risk of developing anxiety, depression, poor emotional regulation or poor communication skills. That’s why sign language at home is a must.

How did you deal with kids who witnessed your arguments at home?

Keeping O feel safe and secure at home and outside doesn’t just mean baby-proofing the house, showing up for her, feeding her, validating her feelings - more than that. From birth, instead of showing ‘I can’t’ attitude, as Deaf parents we show her how capable we are in the home and outside on a daily basis in her first 3 years such as consistently show up to see her needs and respond to her in a timely, different ways to confidently communicate with hearing peers in front of her, showing her there are always solutions to be found, despite the obstacles and challenges we may face. Over the time she would develop security that serves her for a lifetime.

She already know that we are Deaf because her hearing peers (family members, teachers) told her that ‘your Dad and Mum can’t hear’

If O is given too much responsibility (such as interpret for us to communicate with the waiter or schoolteachers) or is expected to be independent at a young age, it teaches her that she cannot rely on us and that she must act much older than her own age in order to be loved. Feeling a burden can be unsafe for Codas.

#montessoriathome #montessoridad #childofdeafadults #coda #codas #feelingsafe #raisingresilientchild #deafculture #learningprocess #hearingdaughter #deafparents

Morning drop offs at childcare can be very hard! During drop offs, O was always clinging to me everyday 🥺

Sneaking off once I see that O has settled in to an activity? BIG NO. This can cause panic when she does look up to see that I’ve suddenly gone. Leaving without a proper goodbye creates a sense that this is the place where I take her, then disappears. I want her to know that I can deal with her emotions 

I often discussed the process of what O might encounter that day.

O really appreciated me trying to explain what’s going on. For example, “I’m going to work and I will be thinking of you all day. You are going to play with your friends, wondering what activities, then I will be back to get you!”

We sometime bring a favourite toy to help her feel close to me and her Mummy throughout the day. 

When I am in a hurry, I try to keep the drop-off 5-10 minutes. Signing goodbye and letting O regulate her emotions in the arms of a trusted Educator is very hard for me!

How about you?

#montessoriathome #montessoridad #montessorichild #fatherhood #secureattachment #childcare #morningdropoffs #selfregulation #emotionregulation #coda #auslan

Business trips can mess up our daily routine and prompt separation anxiety in us.

O does not fully understand the concept of time so it’s best to give her only 3 days’ notice.

We told O when I will be leaving, where I will be going (show the map), what I will be doing (Seeing my Mum, giving a presentation and instructing styled shoots in Florida, meeting people in Ethiopia, and shooting a wedding in France) how I contact her (FaceTime and recorded videos) and when I will return (Mum keeps telling her)

I can’t wait to see her soooooon!

As early as 4 days old, a newborn recognizes their mother’s face. So using sign language at home is never too early. The best way to support your baby’s development of eye contact is by looking at him using authentic sign language (learnt from Deaf teachers not hearing such as ‘baby signs) Babies can see 8-15 inches away, to your face such as feeding/breastfeeding, changing a nappy or showing toys.

There’s no right way to talk to your kids about race. Children are capable of thinking about all sorts of complex topics at a very young age. Even if it’s a difficult topic, it’s important to talk with children about race, because it can be difficult to undo racil bias. We can have a conversation with a child about race that is meaningful to them on their level.

Based on the research: 

At 3 months, a baby’s brain can notice race-based differences. 

By ages 2 to 4, children can internalise racil bias.

Note: Let’s Google if you want to unlearn or want to ask questions.

#montessoriathome #talkingaboutit #unlearn #nevertooearly #norightwaytotalk #letstalknow #fatherhood

Of course, we want O to be kind and considerate, particularly to our family and friends who are important to us (hugs are very positive obviously) but it doesn’t mean we can pressure O to show affection when she doesn’t want to. 

Otherwise we would teach O that she doesn’t have control over her own body, that adults has the right to touch her how they want, when they want, that family members can’t be abusers and much more! Not. That’s a dangerous message for her. 

Like other cultures, hugging is part of Deaf culture BUT I still respect their bodies more than cultures. Seeing, we are still living in the patriarchal world - the male gaze, body policing, assault and much more so 

When we need to greet our family members, I often ask O ‘Want to give a hug or wave at them? The idea is to find something O feels comfortable with. (they are old enough to deal with disappointment anyway)

If she has trouble asserting that boundary, I often talk to our family or friends on her behalf.

Teaching consent is extremely important - I usually sign ‘You are in charge of your body and you can tell us if any adults ask or touch you’

#consent #respecttheirbodies #checkinginfirst #askthemfirst #teachingconsent #kindness #affection #chargeoftheirbody

In fact, our brains are hardwired to notice and fix problems. When I catch myself taking a negative view of situations, it helps to practice cognitive restructuring by reframing the event or experience.  I try to continue to notice the good that change my perspective in parenting.

Few habits I use to slow down, practice gratitude, and notice the good even on tough days - observing what O improves in the home, talking about what O did positively with my wife, asking O ‘What made you happy today?’ which helps us balance out negative experience reflections with positive ones. 

What about your habits? 😘

Hairstyles are an important factor when it comes to expressing the identity of individuals. 
Unsurprisingly there are some schools still banning students from wearing braids, love and twists. Some schools even expelled them.

In the UK , The Equality and Human Rights Commission - under the 2010 Equality Act, which means a person must not be discriminated against because of their hair or hairstyle, associated with their race and ethnicity. At least 15 US states passed similar laws.

I ensure my daughter  doesn’t have to worry about being punished for how she wears her hair. 

In the 1990s, like my Mum, most Black parents were afraid or too tired to stand up to schools, they cared more about our education.

I believe that it’s best to let O experience the natural consequences of her own behaviour. This helps her learn that her actions have consequences. So she will try to be more careful when holding or watching the glass of water to avoid the same accident in the future. When she spilled, she was slightly surprised and signed ‘oops!’ No freeze or flee. She took the tea towel and wiped it up without any prompt

Yelling, threatening and spanking don’t work as consequences. She might refuse to clean the spill if I shame her like ‘what were you thinking?!’ because she won’t learn the natural consequences instead focus on the blame.

#naturalconsequences #withoutprompting #montessoriathome #consciousparenting

O needs to know what we expect. Healthy boundaries helps her to know what is appropriate behaviour and helps to set a tone for her emotional development. It helps her feels safe and secure and encourage her to learn healthy limits.

O still doesn’t comply most of the time when I make a request. That’s totally ok, she is four not 40. Obviously we don’t expect her to get it right away. We have to give her a few friendly reminders otherwise she may have unsafe behaviour. Warm facial expression (same as warm tone) is very important - when she watches my gentle facial expression/signing, I can see she starts to calm down slowly.

@dr.siggie quote:

“Boundaries are not meant to keep your child happy. They’re meant to keep them safe, cared for and to guide their behaviour. Your children have every right to be upset with your boundary. And if they’re upset, that doesn’t mean your boundary is wrong”

ALL children are immature and will misbehave. I’d be very worried if O behaves well all the time.

Facial expression plays an important role in sign language.

Auslan (Australian Sign Language) is O’s first language.

Facial expressions can convey emotions, attitudes, and other nonverbal cues that help to clarify the meaning of a sign.
For example, when asking a question that needs a YES/NO answer your eyebrows tend to be raised. 

Sadly, some hearing parents taught their Deaf child not to use large gestures and facial expressions at the dinner table  or in public because it could look like inappropriate behaviour, shaming them “Stop making your face!”

“Historians and anthropologists have found no evidence that ritualistic forms of physical discipline of children existed in precolonial West African societies prior to the Atlantic slave trade.

West Africans believed that children came from the afterlife, that they were gods or reincarnated ancestors who led profoundly spiritual lives and held extraordinary mystical powers that could be harnessed through ritual practice for the good of the community.

Black parents have legitimate fears about the safety of their children, and the overwhelming majority believe physical discipline is necessary to keep black children out of the streets, out of prison or out of police officers’ sight. And far too many parents argue that “whupping” children is a distinctly black tradition. This belief, however heartfelt, is wrong.”

Stacey Patton, PhD, is an award-winning child advocate, journalist, assistant professor of multimedia journalism at Morgan State University and author of "Spare the Kids: Why Whupping Children Won’t Save Black America." She completed her doctoral training in African-American history at Rutgers University.

O was 2 years old when she started off with a balance bike (no child stabilisers or training wheels)

Balance bikes can help develop gross motor skills, help her transition easily to a pedal bike without training wheels. It’s an essential skill that sets the stage for confident cycling. Training wheels can prevent a child from even attempting to balance.

Importantly, we allow her the space and time to gain confidence.

Not just Christmas, it happens at any events such as work events, networking events, special occasions.

Some call it ‘Dinner Table Experience’, others call it ‘Dinner Table Syndrome’
What does it mean? 

It means when the Deaf or hard of hearing person experiences being left out at the dinner table, because there are a lot of people talking and they’re joking and there’s laughter from the hearing people… they don’t sign at all.

When you want to understand what’s going on - you would ask them to repeat or what they are talking/laughing about.. common responses: “It is not important. Sorry, I will tell you later. Oh, it doesn’t matter!”

Be mindful, Deaf is a spectrum, like myself not every Deaf person can/do lipread. In fact some Deaf people simply doesn’t want to see their hearing family due to communication.

#3 — Top reels of 2023

Keeping O feel safe and secure at home and outside doesn’t just mean baby-proofing the house, showing up for her, feeding her, validating her feelings - more than that. From birth, instead of showing ‘I can’t’ attitude, as Deaf parents we show her how capable we are in the home and outside on a daily basis in her first 3 years such as consistently show up to see her needs and respond to her in a timely, different ways to confidently communicate with hearing peers in front of her, showing her there are always solutions to be found, despite the obstacles and challenges we may face. Over the time she would develop security that serves her for a lifetime.

She already know that we are Deaf because her hearing peers (family members, teachers) told her that ‘your Dad and Mum can’t hear’

If O is given too much responsibility (such as interpret for us to communicate with the waiter or schoolteachers) or is expected to be independent at a young age, it teaches her that she cannot rely on us and that she must act much older than her own age in order to be loved. Feeling a burden can be unsafe for Codas.

Like most parents, Mama and I are struggling during these night because we just want to have our time!

Miss O who is highly sensitive and 3yo has trouble with sleep because she has a very active mind.  It is so hard to calm down her racing thoughts, when her minds are busy processing everything that has gone on throughout the day. She needs to push, run, jump, laugh to calm her nervous system. 

Routine
This lets her know what is expected each night and makes our life a lot easier. Playing with Dad or Mama then reading books consistently.

Choices
Allow her to choose 3 books or pyjama so she feels respected.

Timing
The bedtime routine start early enough to ensure that there is NO RUSHING involved. Expects one hour… (God helps us) Netflix can wait 😉

Hello new followers! Let’s reintroduce myself!

I hail from the UK, bravely migrated to Down Under in 2014 (snake phobia, haven’t seen one yet).

My wife and I are raising a bilingual, bilcultual child who is a Coda (Child of Deaf Adults). Miss O’s life is embedded with Auslan, Deaf culture, as well as Dominican influence which plays a big role in our Montessori journey.

I was born hearing and I became profoundly Deaf when I was 18 months old. My mother decided that British Sign Language should be our main language at home which was the best present I ever had.

Becoming a father is the best thing in my life, it transformed me. As a Black Deaf father, I will continue to play crucial role in my daughter’s emotional, social, physical and brain development.

I enjoy photographing people on film, I am honoured that I am named one of the top wedding photographers in the world by Harper’s Bazaar - check out @ashtonjeanpierre
